SECTION 1 — What is Ecology? Definition & Scope
The foundation of all environmental biology
1.1 Etymology & Basic Definition
The word Ecology comes from the Greek words Oikos (= house / home / dwelling place) and Logos (=
study / science). So literally, ecology means "the study of the home." In scientific terms, it means the study
of the relationships between living organisms and their environment.
Official Definitions
Scientist Definition
Ernst Haeckel (1866)
[Coined the term]
"The science of relations between organisms and their environment, including both biotic
and abiotic factors."
Charles Elton (1927) "Ecology is the scientific study of relationships that determine the distribution and
abundance of organisms."
Odum (1971) "Ecology is the study of the structure and function of nature."
Krebs (1994) "Ecology is the scientific study of the processes governing the distribution and abundance
of organisms, and the interactions between organisms and the transformation and flux of
energy and matter."
1.2 Scope of Ecology
Ecology has a very wide scope — it ranges from studying a single organism and its environment
(autecology) to studying the entire biosphere. Below are the key areas of ecological study:
Area of Study Example Question
Individual organisms and their abiotic environment How does a cactus survive in a desert? (autecology)
Population dynamics Why does the deer population fluctuate in a forest?
Community interactions How do predators, prey, and parasites coexist in the
same area?
Energy flow and nutrient cycling in ecosystems How does energy move from the Sun ® plants ®
herbivores ® carnivores?
Landscape ecology How do spatial patterns affect ecological processes
over large areas?
Global ecology How does climate change affect biodiversity
worldwide?
