5.1 Key Theories of the Origin of Life
Theory of Abiogenesis
(Chemical Evolution)
Life arose from non-living chemicals through a series of chemical reactions.
This is the most scientifically accepted theory. Also called the
Oparin-Haldane Hypothesis (1924–1929).
Oparin-Haldane
Hypothesis
A.I. Oparin (Russia, 1924) and J.B.S. Haldane (UK, 1929) independently
proposed that the early Earth had a reducing atmosphere (rich in H2, CH4,
NH3, H2O) and no free oxygen (O2). UV radiation and lightning triggered
chemical reactions forming organic molecules ® "primordial soup" ®
protocells ® life.
Miller-Urey Experiment
(1953)
Stanley Miller and Harold Urey EXPERIMENTALLY PROVED
Oparin-Haldane theory. They recreated early Earth conditions in a lab: gases
(H2, CH4, NH3, H2O) + electric sparks (simulating lightning) ® amino acids
formed! This was the first experimental evidence that organic molecules can
form from inorganic chemicals under primitive Earth conditions.
Panspermia Theory Life or its building blocks (organic molecules) arrived on Earth from outer
space via meteorites or comets. Evidence: amino acids found in Murchison
meteorite (1969). This does NOT explain how life first formed — only how it
may have reached Earth.
Theory of Special
Creation
Life was created by a supernatural force. Not scientifically testable —
rejected in mainstream science but important historically.
n EXAM TIP: Miller-Urey Experiment (1953) is VERY FREQUENTLY asked in UGC NET. Remember:
they used reducing atmosphere + electric sparks ® produced amino acids. Also remember Oparin
