SECTION 6 — Theory of Evolution
How life diversified — Lamarck, Darwin & Modern Synthesis
After life first appeared (~3.5 billion years ago), it evolved — meaning it changed over generations,
eventually producing the millions of species alive today. Understanding evolution is essential for ecology
because the adaptations of organisms determine how they interact with their environment.
6.1 Lamarckism (Theory of Acquired Characteristics) — 1809
Proposed by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck (French biologist). Two key principles:
Use and Disuse Organs that are used frequently develop and get stronger; organs that are not
used weaken and disappear. Example: giraffes stretched their necks to reach
leaves ® necks became longer over generations.
Inheritance of
Acquired
Characteristics
Traits acquired during an organism's lifetime are passed to offspring. Example: a
blacksmith's strong arms would be inherited by his children.
n Lamarckism is DISPROVED. Weismann (1892) cut off tails of mice for 22 generations — offspring
were still born with tails. Acquired characteristics are NOT inherited because they don't change
DNA.
6.2 Darwinism (Theory of Natural Selection) — 1859
Charles Darwin published "On the Origin of Species" in 1859. His theory is based on 5 key observations:
Principle Explanation
1. Overproduction All species produce more offspring than can survive (e.g., a fish lays thousands of
eggs).
2. Variation Individuals within a population vary in their traits (size, colour, speed, immunity).
3. Struggle for Existence Resources are limited ® competition for food, mates, space. Not all can survive.
4. Survival of the Fittest
(Natural Selection)
Individuals with favourable variations survive and reproduce more. "Fittest" means
best adapted, NOT strongest.
5. Heredity Favourable traits are passed to offspring. Over many generations ® new species
evolve.
6.3 Modern Synthetic Theory (Neo-Darwinism)
Darwinism + Genetics = Modern Synthetic Theory (developed in 1930s–1950s by Dobzhansky, Huxley,
Mayr, Simpson). It added the molecular mechanism to Darwin's observations:
• Mutations — Random changes in DNA provide raw variation
• Genetic Recombination — Sexual reproduction creates new gene combinations
• Natural Selection — Acts on the variation (Darwin's mechanism)
• Genetic Drift — Random changes in allele frequency in small populations
• Gene Flow — Movement of alleles between populations via migration
• Reproductive Isolation — Prevents gene flow ® new species form
