SECTION 7 — Speciation
How one species becomes two — the engine of biodiversity
7.1 What is Speciation?
Speciation is the evolutionary process by which one or more new biological species arise from an
ancestral population. It is the primary mechanism of biodiversity generation on Earth.
Key Terms You Must Know
n Species:
A group of organisms that can interbreed and produce viable, fertile offspring, and are reproductively
isolated from other groups. (Biological Species Concept — Ernst Mayr, 1942)
n Gene Pool:
The total collection of genes (and their alleles) in a population at a given time.
n Reproductive Isolation:
Barriers that prevent interbreeding between populations. Crucial for speciation.
n Allopatry:
Populations living in different geographical areas (allo = other, patria = homeland).
n Sympatry:
Populations living in the same geographical area (sym = same, patria = homeland).
n Parapatry:
Populations living in adjacent areas with a narrow zone of contact.
n Peripatry:
A small peripheral population becomes isolated from the main population.
n Adaptive Radiation:
From one ancestral species, multiple species evolve rapidly to fill different ecological niches. Classic
example: Darwin's Finches in Galapagos Islands.
