7.2 Types of Speciation in Detail
Page 13 | UGC NET Env. Sciences — Unit 3.1 | JRF Guide
Allopatric Speciation
Most common type. A physical barrier (mountain, river, ocean) divides a population. Gene flow stops.
Each isolated group evolves independently under different selection pressures and accumulates genetic
differences. Eventually they become reproductively isolated even if barriers are removed.
Example: Darwin's Finches (Galapagos), Squirrels separated by the Grand Canyon
Sympatric Speciation
New species arise within the same geographic area. No physical barrier. Common mechanism: polyploidy
(doubling of chromosomes — common in plants). Also through ecological specialisation or sexual
selection.
Example: Polyploid wheat (Triticum), Apple maggot fly in USA
Parapatric Speciation
Adjacent populations with a narrow hybrid zone. Some gene flow occurs at the border but selection
pressures are different in each area. Reproductive isolation evolves despite limited gene flow.
Example: Greenish Warbler (Phylloscopus trochiloides) around Tibetan Plateau
Peripatric Speciation
A small peripheral population becomes isolated from the main population. Strong genetic drift + selection
in small group ® rapid divergence. Also called Founder Effect speciation.
Example: Island species from mainland ancestors
7.3 Reproductive Isolation Mechanisms
Reproductive isolation is the key to speciation. It is classified into Pre-zygotic (before fertilisation) and
Post-zygotic (after fertilisation) barriers:
Type Mechanism Example
PRE-ZYGOTIC BARRIERS (prevent mating / fertilisation)
Habitat isolation Species live in different habitats in same area Two frog species — one in ponds, one
in trees
Temporal isolation Species breed at different times
(seasons/times of day)
Oak trees release pollen at different
times
Behavioural isolation Different mating calls, dances, pheromones Fireflies with different flash patterns
Mechanical isolation Incompatible genitalia or flower structures Flowers shaped for different pollinators
Gametic isolation Sperm cannot fertilise eggs of another species Sea urchins — chemical barriers on
egg surface
POST-ZYGOTIC BARRIERS (offspring fail or are infertile)
Hybrid inviability Hybrid embryo does not develop or dies early Some Drosophila (fruit fly) crosses
